"Svensen H., Schmidbauer N., Roscher M., Stordal F., Planke S.","Contact metamorphism, halocarbons, and environmental crises of the past",2009,"Environmental Chemistry","6","6",,"466","471",,,10.1071/EN09118,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-73249137116&partnerID=40&md5=8b15846c7d542287960c0212e290d565","Physics of Geological Processes (PGP), University of Oslo, PO Box 1048 Blindern, NO-0316 Oslo, Norway; Norwegian Institute for Air Research, PO Box 100, NO-2027 Kjeller, Norway; Department of Geosciences, University of Oslo, PO Box 1047 Blindern, NO-0316 Oslo, Norway; Volcanic Basin Petroleum Research (VBPR), Oslo Research Park, NO-0349 Oslo, Norway","Svensen, H., Physics of Geological Processes (PGP), University of Oslo, PO Box 1048 Blindern, NO-0316 Oslo, Norway; Schmidbauer, N., Norwegian Institute for Air Research, PO Box 100, NO-2027 Kjeller, Norway; Roscher, M., Physics of Geological Processes (PGP), University of Oslo, PO Box 1048 Blindern, NO-0316 Oslo, Norway; Stordal, F., Department of Geosciences, University of Oslo, PO Box 1047 Blindern, NO-0316 Oslo, Norway; Planke, S., Volcanic Basin Petroleum Research (VBPR), Oslo Research Park, NO-0349 Oslo, Norway","What triggered the largest know mass extinction at the Permian-Triassic boundary 252 million years ago, when 95% of the species in the oceans disappeared? New geological data suggest that eruptions of carbon (CH 4, CO2) and halocarbon (CH3Cl and CH 3Br) gases from the vast sedimentary basins of east Siberia could have triggered a period with global warming (5°-10°C) and terrestrial mass extinction. The gases were generated during contact metamorphism of sedimentary rocks around 1200°C hot igneous intrusions. One of the suggested end-Permian extinction mechanisms is the extreme ultraviolet radiation (UV-B) caused by a prolonged destruction of stratospheric ozone induced by the emitted halocarbons. This hypothesis is supported by a new set of experiments, where natural rock salt samples from Siberia were heated to 275°C. Among the gases generated during heating are methyl chloride (CH3Cl) and methyl bromide (CH3Br). These findings open up new possibilities for investigating ancient environmental crises. © CSIRO 2009.",,"contact metamorphism; geological record; global warming; halocarbon; igneous intrusion; mass extinction; methyl bromide; methyl chloride; ozone; paleoenvironment; Permian-Triassic boundary; rock salt; sedimentary basin; stratosphere; ultraviolet B radiation; Siberia",,,,,,"Wignall, P.B., Large igneous provinces and mass extinctions (2001) Earth Science Reviews, 53 (1-2), pp. 1-33. , DOI 10.1016/S0012-8252(00)00037-4, PII S0012825200000374; Courtillot, V.E., Renne, P.R., On the ages of flood basalt events (2003) Comptes Rendus - Geoscience, 335 (1), pp. 113-140. , DOI 10.1016/S1631-0713(03)00006-3; Svenson, H., Planke, S., Maithe-Sorensen, A., Jamtveit, B., Myklebust, R., Eidem, T.R., Rey, S.S., Release of methane from a volcanic basin as a mechanism for initial Eocene global warming (2004) Nature, 429 (6991), pp. 542-545. , DOI 10.1038/nature02566; Svensen, H., Planke, S., Polozov, A.G., Schmidbauer, N., Corfu, F., Podladchikov, Y.Y., Jamtveit, B., Siberian gas venting and the end-Permian environmental crisis (2009) Earth Planet. Sci. Lett., 277, p. 490. , doi:10.1016/J.EPSL.2008.11.015; Svensen, H., Planke, S., Chevallier, L., Malthe-Sorenssen, A., Corfu, F., Jamtveit, B., Hydrothermal venting of greenhouse gases triggering Early Jurassic global warming (2007) Earth and Planetary Science Letters, 256 (3-4), pp. 554-566. , DOI 10.1016/j.epsl.2007.02.013, PII S0012821X07000763; Zachos, J.C., Rohl, U., Schellenberg, S.A., Sluijs, A., Hodell, D.A., Kelly, D.C., Thomas, E., Kroon, D., Paleoclimate: Rapid acidification of the ocean during the paleocene-eocene thermal maximum (2005) Science, 308 (5728), pp. 1611-1615. , DOI 10.1126/science.1109004; Kennett, J.P., Stott, L.D., Abrupt deep-sea warming, palaeoceanographic changes and benthic 